That change wouldn't affect anything about the data you collected; it's just a minor change to how we solicited their ratings.  I'm thinking 2 things.  First, even if a participant thinks after the negative rare block that the rare critter is more negative, they might click around 20 for the common critter, then when they get to the rare critter, they won't know exactly where they clicked for the common, so even if they think they are indicating a higher negative rating for the rare critter, they might not actually click that way.  That is supported by the fact that our effects are small.  The differences in ratings are not usually very large....just a few points (you wouldn't expect them to be huge differences).  The other thing that occurs to me is that we care about the difference between Rare and Common critters.  If they always evaluate the common critter first, then a reviewer could argue that the order of ratings is confounded with any differences between rare and common.  I think there are two options:

Place two rating scales under each word. One for the common critter and one for the rare critter.  This would be the most similar to what we're doing now, just eliminating potential order effects.
Keep one rating scale per word, but put the rare critter on one side and the common critter on the other so that a score of 50 indicates the same rating for both.  Anything other than 50 indicates a leaning toward one or the other.  

If you go with option 1, you are only going to improve the measurement of participants' attitudes and you can still include the first 11 datasets in your analysis for either FYP and Thesis.  If you finish collecting FYP data this way, you could not combine them later.  This is important because your correlations with the depression scores will require a large sample so it would be better to make the switch now.  
